# Fab Tabs Shop Notes — Blog Setup Guide
### blog.primochops.com, hosted free on Cloudflare Pages, published via GitHub

## What you're getting

8 files, ready to go live:
- `index.html` — the post list / homepage
- `posts/3-bolt-vs-single-bolt-exhaust-flange.html` — one real, finished post to start with
- `style.css` — the shared design (shop-tag cards over your psychedelic swirl background)
- `swirl-lines.svg` — the tiled linework pattern used in the background
- `rss.xml` — feed so people (and Google) can subscribe/track updates
- `sitemap.xml` + `robots.txt` — so search engines crawl it properly

No build tools, no framework, no `npm install`. Every page is a plain HTML file. Publishing a new post is: write the file, add two lines to two other files, push.

---

## Step 1 — Put it on GitHub

1. Go to [github.com](https://github.com) and create a free account if you don't have one
2. Click **New repository**. Name it something like `fabtabs-blog`. Keep it **Public** (needed for the free Cloudflare Pages tier). Don't initialize with a README — you're uploading files directly.
3. On the new empty repo's page, click **uploading an existing file**
4. Drag in all 7 files/folders from the download (keep the `posts/` folder structure intact)
5. Commit directly to the `main` branch

That's it — your blog now exists in a GitHub repo, nothing live yet.

---

## Step 2 — Connect it to Cloudflare Pages

You already have a Cloudflare account from the DNS migration, so this reuses it.

1. Log into [dash.cloudflare.com](https://dash.cloudflare.com)
2. In the left sidebar, find **Workers & Pages** → **Create** → **Pages** → **Connect to Git**
3. Authorize Cloudflare to access your GitHub account, then select the `fabtabs-blog` repo
4. Build settings: leave **Framework preset** as "None," leave the **Build command** blank, set **Build output directory** to `/` (just a single slash — this is a plain static site, nothing to build)
5. Click **Save and Deploy**

Cloudflare will give you a working URL like `fabtabs-blog.pages.dev` within a minute or two. Open it and confirm the blog loads correctly before moving on.

---

## Step 3 — Point blog.primochops.com at it

1. Still in Cloudflare, go to your Pages project → **Custom domains** → **Set up a custom domain**
2. Enter `blog.primochops.com` → **Continue** → **Activate domain**

Because your DNS is already on Cloudflare, it will typically add the required CNAME record automatically. If it doesn't:
1. Go to **DNS** for the `primochops.com` zone
2. Add a record: Type **CNAME**, Name `blog`, Target `fabtabs-blog.pages.dev`, Proxy status **Proxied** (orange cloud)

Give it a few minutes, then visit `https://blog.primochops.com` — it should load your blog with a valid SSL certificate, same as the rest of your Cloudflare-managed domain.

---

## Step 4 — Publish your next post (the actual workflow going forward)

Every time you write a new post, you're touching **3 files**:

### 1. Create the post file
Copy `posts/3-bolt-vs-single-bolt-exhaust-flange.html`, rename it to match your new post (e.g. `posts/heavy-metal-vs-mild-steel.html`), and edit:
- The `<title>` and `<meta name="description">` tags at the top
- The category stamp, date, and heading inside `<article>`
- The body content

### 2. Add it to `index.html`
Copy the `<li class="tag-card">...</li>` block, paste it **above** the "NEW POST TEMPLATE" comment (newest post goes first), and edit the link, stamp, date, title, and excerpt.

### 3. Add it to `rss.xml` and `sitemap.xml`
Same idea — copy the template block in each file, fill in your new post's details, paste above the comment.

Then push the changed files back to GitHub (drag-and-drop the updated files into the repo again, or use GitHub Desktop if you want a proper local workflow later). **Cloudflare Pages redeploys automatically within about a minute of any push** — no redeploy button to remember.

