## A note on the design

The background is an original tiled swirl pattern in your site's palette — pink, teal, gold, and periwinkle blue, with hand-drawn-style black linework, matching the psychedelic look on primochops.com itself (built from scratch, not copied from any stock image, so there's no licensing risk). Since that pattern is busy, the header, each post preview, and the full article body all sit on solid cream panels — styled like shop tags and work tickets — so text stays easy to read against it. Headlines use a bold condensed face (Oswald) like stamped signage; dates, categories, and links use a monospace face (JetBrains Mono) like a part number stencil.

---

## What this doesn't do (yet)

- **No tag/category archive pages.** At low volume (a post every few weeks), the single homepage list covers it. If you get past ~15-20 posts, say the word and I'll build category pages.
- **No comments.** Intentional — keeps this zero-maintenance. If you want reader engagement, Instagram is still the better venue for that.
- **No search.** Same reasoning — not worth the complexity until there's a real archive to search through.

---

## Quick sanity checklist once it's live

1. `https://blog.primochops.com` loads and looks right on both desktop and phone
2. `https://blog.primochops.com/posts/3-bolt-vs-single-bolt-exhaust-flange.html` loads directly
3. `https://blog.primochops.com/rss.xml` shows valid XML in the browser
4. Submit `https://blog.primochops.com/sitemap.xml` to Google Search Console **as a new, separate property** from primochops.com (subdomains are treated as distinct in Search Console)
5. Add a link to the blog somewhere on primochops.com itself (a nav link or footer link) — this is what actually passes SEO benefit between the two, since a subdomain doesn't automatically share authority with the main domain
